e lives of the Irish in unexpected ways, and that the rise of writing and the spread of print were central to an understanding of those changes which have previously only been understood to have been the result of conquest and colonisation. This is a book which will be read not only by those interested in the Irish past but by all those who are concerned with the impact of communications media on social change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBooks and readingzIrelandxHistoryy16th century. 0aBooks and readingzIrelandxHistoryy17th century. 0aPrintingzIrelandxHistoryy16th century. 0aPrintingzIrelandxHistoryy17th century. 0aSocial changezIrelandxHistoryy16th century. 0aSocial changezIrelandxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  abooksellers.  acolonization.  aearly modern Ireland.  aidea transmission.  aintellectual commodity.  amaterial commodity.  aprint technology.  aprinted ephemera.  aprinted word.  asocial meaning.  atraditional exchange economy.1 aGillespie, Raymond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779432140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847794321423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847794321/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles